<HEADLINE> World Bank Offers Help To Solve Angola's Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A visiting World Bank official
today pledged the bank's "full support" to Angola which she said
was torn apart by an "economic crisis."
</P>
<P>
Katherine Marshall, director of the Southern African
Department of the World Bank, said at the end of her week-long
fact-finding trip that the crisis was caused by overstretched
expenditure of long years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Marshall said the World
Bank is formulating an aid package to help Angola restore its
national economy.
</P>
<P>
She urged the Angolan people to devote "the greatest
possible effort" to helping settle this crisis along with the
government and the international community.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, she said she had discussed with Angolan
leaders on scope of the crisis, measures to find a solution, and
what role the international community should play in finding a
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official had also toured several provinces of
the Southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
