<HEADLINE> Drought Drives 800,000 Somalians To Ethiopian Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A six-months-old drought has
driven an estimated 800,000 Somali nomads to migrate from
northwestern Somalia to areas bordering Ethiopia, said a report
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The report from the Djibouti-based Horn of Africa Development
Agency said the drought, centered in the Sol and Sanaag regions,
has so far killed an estimated 500,000 heads of cattle.
</P>
<P>
Sol and Sanaag were also the center of a severe drought in 1974
when 140,000 people were moved from the region with the help of a
soviet airlift to southern somalia.
</P>
<P>
During the drought twelve years ago, 18,000 people were killed
by famine and livestock losses were devastating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
