<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Firms Responsible for 70% of UK's Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized British
companies are responsible for nearly three-quarters of industrial
air pollution in Britain, according to BMS Bossard, the management
consultants.
</P>
<P>
The consultancy, which advises some of Britain's largest
companies on the issue, claimed that only 12 percent of Britain's
3.5 million small and medium-sized enterprises incorporate
environmental considerations into business plans.
</P>
<P>
Ron Brender, managing director of the consultancy, said
research by the British Chamber of Commerce suggested that only
one in five of smaller companies had encountered pressure from
their customers to improve their environmental performance.
</P>
<P>
While big, blue chip companies were aware of public opinion and
shareholder pressure, the emphasis in smaller enterprises was on
getting business in rather than worrying about the environment
around them, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the continuing failure of smaller businesses to
take environmental issues seriously was understandable, given
limited staff and resources.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that without a change of attitudes, the sector
would remain a significant source of industrial pollution.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UK accounted for one-fifth of man-made
emissions of carbon dioxide in Europe, compared with 12 percent
from France and 13 percent from Italy.
</P>
<P>
BMS Bossard claimed that UK regulations on planning and
emissions from business premises were not strict enough.
</P>
<P>
Brender added that small and medium-sized businesses are vital
to Britain's long-term economic health and it is critical that
they take very seriously environmental issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
