<HEADLINE> Washington, Nicosia Agree on Overall Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and the United States
have agreed that there should be an overall approach to all key
issues composing the Cyprus problem and that all fundamental
questions should be on the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
This was stated here today by Cyprus Foreign Minister Alecos
Michaelides and U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Richard Boucher, after a
meeting at the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, the two diplomats said they exchanged
views on the forthcoming visit to Nicosia by Richard Holbrooke,
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for European and Canadian
Affairs, which is expected to take place in early February, and on
recent visits to Cyprus by foreign officials, including European
Union envoys.
</P>
<P>
Boucher said the U.S. would "address those (fundamental) issues
but we're going to address them together because we believe that
is the best way to go forward."
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Cypriot foreign minister stressed that "we
have made it clear to all that we do not accept a partial
discussion of the Cyprus problem, but we want an overall approach
to achieve common ground before negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Michaelides noted that the Greek Cypriot side's position on
this issue was now widely accepted.
</P>
<P>
Boucher noted the U.S. strategy in Cyprus was to get together
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash "but on a basis that gives them some chance of success."
</P>
<P>
He said he would continue his meetings in Nicosia and efforts
"to set a comprehensive basis for agreement on the fundamental
issues."
</P>
<P>
Both Michaelides and Boucher denied press reports that
Washington had worked out a plan for solving the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides said the only decision by the U.S. was to address
the substance of the Cyprus problem with meetings in Nicosia,
Athens and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has stepped up peace efforts on Cyprus problem since
last December.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard Beattie visited the island on
December 4, 1995, resulting in a document in which Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash made a shift in his position by agreeing to
support European Union membership of a federal Cyprus, provided
the sovereignty and political equality of the Turkish Cypriots
are recognized.
</P>
<P>
But the document was rejected by the Greek Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, the U.S. assistant secretary of state, has stated
that he would deal with the Cyprus problem after achieving a
solution to the Bosnian crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a recent statement, he promised to make 1996 a year of the
"big push" on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, who was said to be resigning in mid February, was
originally scheduled to visit Cyprus, Greece and Turkey between
January 23-27 but his trip was postponed for what he said the
political situation in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey militarily
intervened following an Athen-backed Greek Cypriot coup seeking
union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
