<HEADLINE> Afro-Arab Parliamentary Conference Opens in Amman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The seventh Afro-Arab
Parliamentary Dialogue conference opened here today with the aim
of coordinating Arab and African stands on issues of mutual
interest.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan opened the three-day conference,
which was attended by parliament speakers and deputies from 29
Arab and African countries, including Jordan.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the king called for Afro-Arab cooperation to
solve disputes among states by peaceful means and stand firm
against those resorting to force to settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to tackle the Yemen-Eritrean
conflict over three Red Sea islands.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, participants will discuss proposals to
activate Afro-Arab dialogue, tackle conflicts in Africa and
the Arab World.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to find an appropriate mechanism to
settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on efforts to launch Afro-Arab
cooperation to make the two regions free of nuclear and mass
destruction weapons, Radio Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
Participants will review the impact of the application of the
World Trade Organization (WTO), formerly the General Agreement on
Trade and Tariffs (GATT), on African and Arab countries'
economies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Arab parliamentarians will hold a special
session Thursday to discuss the U.S. Congress decision to move the
American embassy to Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Following the U.S. Congress decision to transfer the embassy
to Jerusalem last year, the Arab Parliamentary Union called for an urgent
meeting to discuss the move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
