<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GSS Chief Resigns after Rabin Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Israeli
General Security Services (GSS) this afternoon handed in his
resignation to Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres, and the
latter accepted the resignation, Israel Television reported.
</P>
<P>
The head of GSS, known as "K," has been criticized for his role
in failing to protect the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin when
he was assassinated in Tel Aviv on November 4 last year.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Shamgar Commission of Inquiry, established to
investigate the assassination of Rabin, sent the head of GSS a
warning letter, saying that he could be harmed by testimony given
by the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after Rabin's assassination, "K" had offered to
resign, but that was at the time rejected by Peres, who said that
he would not take any decision on firing "K" until the Shamgar
commission publishes its findings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the GSS chief's attorney invited several
witnesses to appear before the Shamgar Commission, in an attempt
to clear his name, which appears to have failed.
</P>
<P>
Six other senior GSS and police officers also received warning
letters from the Shamgar Commission, and it is not known yet
whether there will be more resignations.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was shot at point-blank range by Yigal Amir, a Jewish
extremist who wanted to stop the peace process, near his car
after participating in a massive peace rally in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The Shamgar Commission has been holding a series of hearings
to investigate the first assassination of an Israeli prime
minister in the history of the State of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
