<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Stresses Support for U.N. Resolution 425 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Canadian House of
Representatives Gilbert Adolph Parent reiterated here today his
country's support for the implementation of U.N. Security Council
resolution 425, which calls Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Parent, who arrived here Sunday morning, today held separate
meetings with Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berri, President Elias
Hrawi and Prime Minister Rafik al Hariri, after a meeting with
Maronite Patriarch Nasrallah Boutros Sfeir, spiritual leader of
Lebanon's Maronite Catholic community.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his meeting with Lebanese President Hrawi this
afternoon, Parent told reporters that "on this occasion I want to
reaffirm Canada's support for resolution 425." He added that "we
always hope that Lebanon extends its sovereignty to the southern
part of your country and enjoys independence on all its lands."
</P>
<P>
"Canada's position does not change," the Canadian speaker
noted.
</P>
<P>
On his country's stand on the Palestinian refugees in Lebanon,
Parent pointed out that Canada has accepted a number of the
Palestinian refugees from Lebanon, and stressed his country's
willingness to accept more.
</P>
<P>
But on what is taking place between the Palestinians and
Lebanon, Parent said, this issue should be decided between the
two sides, and he was optimistic that in the coming months and the
next few years good solutions will be found for all the states.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that peace will be achieved between Syria
and Israel and finally between Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"In the past years peace was established between Israel and
Egypt, now there has been an agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians, and we hope an agreement will be achieved between
Israel and Syria and Lebanon also joins them."
</P>
<P>
He said his country is trying to contribute to the Middle East
peace because "the peace here makes it easy to make the peace in
the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
Following his talks with Berri, Parent underlined his country's
support for Lebanon's sovereignty and independence within its
internationally recognized borders.
</P>
<P>
Calling on Lebanon to attend the multilateral talks which will
be sponsored by Canada and in which the problem of Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon will be discussed, Parent said Lebanon should
not be afraid of that talks.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his country's readiness to make a serious
contribution to the finding of a solution for this problem.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are about 500,000 Palestinian
refugees living in Lebanon, most of them are residing in dozens of
refugee camps scattered all over the country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism on the prospect of achieving peace in the
region, especially in the light of the resumption of the
Syrian-Israeli peace talks just before the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Parent also expressed his belief that progresses on the
Syrian-Israeli track will definitely reflect positively on the
Lebanese-Israeli track, in view of the "firm relations" between
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if peace does not prevail in the Middle East
region, there will be no peace in any part of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian house speaker also stressed his country's concern
on a realization of comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
