<HEADLINE> Teachers On Strike In Luanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Luanda's primary and high
schools closed doors today in a massive strike held by teachers
demanding higher pay and better working conditions.
</P>
<P>
The strike, to be "indefinite until teachers' demands are
met," was held in the Angolan capital on the fifth day of the new
semester.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by a general meeting of Teachers' Union
in Luanda on Saturday. Its spokesman said the strike was aimed,
among other things, at urging the authorities to approve the
regulations for teachers and pegging teachers' salaries to the
U.S. dollar amid soaring inflation.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' demands include the provisions of books to the
libraries and of equipment to the laboratories so as to improve
the working conditions of various schools.
</P>
<P>
The school teachers raised their demands to the government in
their first-ever strike held in August last year but got no
response, said a spokesman of the Teachers Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
