<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki Orders Independent Inquiry into Bugging Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Claims of National
Intelligence Agency (NIA) agents spying on top police officials
might have to referred to an independent investigator, South
Africa's First Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Pretoria, Mbeki said whether
or not this is necessary would be determined by a meeting of
security ministers and intelligence agency heads this week.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said: "we need to take a decision whether it is
exclusively a matter of an intelligence investigation or whether
it is a matter that requires independent intervention, which is
possible."
</P>
<P>
The Johannesburg-based Star newspaper last week reported the
entire top structure of the police, including National
Commissioner George Fivaz, was being spied on. It quoted unnamed
sources saying the NIA had assigned this task to Vlakplaas police
base former commander Dirk Coetzee.
</P>
<P>
However, the NIA denied it has been spying on top police
officers and that Coetzee has been assigned to such surveillance.
Coetzee himself also denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that the allegations had to be taken
seriously, Mbeki said a commissioner might have to be appointed
to investigate them.
</P>
<P>
"Because if there is some rogue element out there, they are
not going to come to you to say 'sorry, it was me,'" he added.
</P>
<P>
The proposed meeting of security ministers and intelligence
agency heads called by Mbeki later in the week would have to
decide whether the investigation should be conducted by security
branches.
</P>
<P>
To this regard, Mbeki stressed that there has to be
cooperation between all the country's security and intelligence
services, saying this is vital to ensure that all of them,
including the police, function effectively.
</P>
<P>
"They really ought to know: who has got access to bugs? and
who is the most likely culprit if it is not the secret services
themselves?"
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the NIA ought to be lending as much support as they
could to the police to do their work, said Mbeki, adding, "if
some bug is found somewhere, it ought to be a matter of joint
consent."
</P>
<P>
The bugging case has already caused wild reactions from
political parties in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The African National Congress (ANC) last week said it
questioned the veracity of the allegations, saying it was
inconceivable the NIA and police were in competition.
</P>
<P>
"Both the NIA and police remain committed to the same
objective: the defense of our democracy," the ANC said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
While the National Party said the matter was developing into a
major scandal and called for an urgent investigation by the
parliamentary committee on intelligence.
</P>
<P>
Parliament's joint standing committee on intelligence,
however, announced at the weekend it would launch its own
investigation into the allegations that the NIA is spying on top
police officers.
</P>
<P>
Committee chairwoman Lindiwe Sisulu said in terms of the
Intelligence Service Control Act, the committee could order an
investigation regarding any complaint received from a member of
the public.
</P>
<P>
"The committee is accountable to the public and requests of
this nature require it to respond," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
