<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Child Welfare Institute, Home for Orphans (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Han Weicheng, who was director of the institute when Zhang
Shuyun worked there, said that Zhang had ulterior motives when
she dirted the institute's name by inventing stories. It is
astonishing that Human Rights Watch/Asia took Zhang's rumors as
news stories and spread them everywhere, although they have been
refuted by facts, He added.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that the Shanghai municipal government and other parts
of society have long paid great attention to the orphans at the
institute since the founding of new China.
</P>
<P>
The municipal budget for the institute has been increasing over
the past several years, reaching nearly six million yuan in 1995,
along with more than two million yuan donated by individuals
and institutions, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
The children with normal intelligence at the institute are sent
to nearby primary and middle schools, and, after returning to the
institute, are given further guidance in the evening to help them
cope with problems they may encounter in learning, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
In order to help the overall development of disabled orphans,
the institute set up a 2,500 sq m special school with a playground
covering 1,200 sq m and a 70-sq-m Children's Park, and provides
special education for mentally-retarded children, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zuqing said that the children come from all parts of the
country. Sometimes boys make up the bigger proportion of children
there, sometimes girls do.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the mortality rate of the children, Shi
explained that those adopted by the institute are mostly disabled
and have severe congenital disorders or physiological defects, and
noted that, "Thanks to treatment and care provided by the
institute, the mortality rate has stood at 4 percent in recent
years."
</P>
<P>
As for the whereabouts of the children, Shi said that healthy
orphans, or those with diseases but who are able to work will
remain at the institute until adulthood, and then some will get
married and embark on a new career.
</P>
<P>
Youths above the age of 16 who have lost the ability to work
because of physiological defects will be transferred to other
welfare institutes for further care, education, and
rehabilitation, he explained.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some orphans have been adopted by families going
through proper formalities in the legal system.
</P>
<P>
Many workers at the institute who knew Zhang Shuyun expressed
indignation at Human Rights Watch/Asia in its fabrication of the
stories based on Zhang's unfounded accusations attempting to
slander the Chinese people and deceive the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
They said that fabrication and spreading of the lies hurt the
staff and workers in the institute and reveal overt hostility
towards the Chinese people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
