<HEADLINE> Elections Office Collects Data on Voters Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Elections Office said
today it has sent its officers to various provinces to collect
data concerning the voters registration exercise before a
recommendation can be made to the cabinet to extend the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Director of the office Rabson Mwansa told reporters here that
election officers, who are touring the nine provinces, will give
a detailed report before the exercise closes on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to get a clear picture of the registration exercise
and the officers will report the actual figures prevailing before
steps concerning the extension of registration period can be
considered," Mwansa said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated only 20 percent of the eligible voters have
registered since the registration exercise began on December 12
last year. The 30-day exercise has been marred by unprecedented
apathy so far.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that his office has already made a number of
recommendations to the cabinet which has authority to decide on
the extension of the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties recently proposed to the government that
elections can only be held when an estimated 4.6 million eligible
voters are registered.
</P>
<P>
But National Secretary of the ruling Movement for Multi-Party
Democracy (mmd) Michael Sata has insisted, "We will go ahead with
elections this year when the voters registration exercise is over
whether people have registered or not." 
</P>
</TEXT>
