<HEADLINE> Japan's Government Names Hashimoto as Premier Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Japan's three
ruling coalition parties today formally endorsed Ryutaro Hashimoto
as their joint candidate for the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, the president of the Liberal Democratic Party(LDP)
and the current trade minister, will succeed the outgoing Prime
Minister Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the Social Democratic
Party(SDP), who announced his resignation on January 5.
</P>
<P>
He is certain to be named in a parliamentary vote on January 11
as the new prime minister because of the coalition's solid
majority in both houses of the Diet.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, 58, will be the fifth prime minister and the first
LDP premier in two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
The LDP was ousted from power in 1993 after a series of
scandals for the first time since its founding in 1955. It
returned to the ruling camp in June 1994 after forming the current
coalition with the SDP and Sakigake with Murayama as prime
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
