<HEADLINE> Lithuanian President Rejects Ministers' Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Lithuanian President Algirdas
Brazauskas rejected today resignation of Foreign Minister Povilas
Gylys and Defense Minister Linas Linkevicius, reports reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they were told to continue to perform their duties
pending a final decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers tendered their resignations last Friday to
show their dissatisfaction with Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius.
</P>
<P>
They regard as unethical the conduct of the head of the
cabinet, who, with the knowledge of the deplorable financial
status of the Lithuanian Innovations Joint-Stock Bank, withdrew
his deposits from it two days before its activities were suspended.
</P>
<P>
The incident roused a storm of indignation among hundreds of
thousands of Lithuanian citizens, who lost their savings with
crisis-ridden commercial banks of the country.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with the president today, the defense minister
told reporters that he did not withdraw his resignation petition
while the foreign minister only said that he would remain at his
post.
</P>
<P>
However, 16 other cabinet members have stated that they
disapproved of the conduct of their two colleagues and "are fully
resolved to continue to work under the premier's leadership."
</P>
