<HEADLINE> Shanghai Child Welfare Institute, Home for Orphans (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A two-year-old girl, Tang Linping, could be seen playing on a
slide. The director, Sheng Xiaowei, said, "She has a congenital
heart disease and had an operation half a month ago. She is now
able play like normal children."
</P>
<P>
The reporters were shown the rules and regulations on the wall
of the Infant Ward. These included: "Responsibility of the Head of
the Infant Ward", "Safety and Management of Children's Living
Space", "Duty of Child-care Workers on Night Shift", and
"Responsibilities of Child-care Workers."
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhuqing, director of the institute, said that the
institute uses these rules and regulations to instill
responsibility in child-care workers to see that orphans grow up
in a healthy way.
</P>
<P>
Zhou pointed out that anyone in the institute who leaves his
(or her) post without permission, or who beats and or scolds the
children, will be subject to severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
In one room, there was a horizontal scroll on which was
written, "Spreading love in the hearts of children." In another
room, young children were playing table tennis. When they saw a
group of foreign reporters, they were delighted and shouted,
"Foreigners!" "Foreigners!"
</P>
<P>
When "New York Times" reporter Patrick Tyler asked
five-year-old Tang Yuanqing about her name, the little girl,
dressed in green sweater and red trousers, just giggled, and
didn't answer. She playfully called the visitor "Old bear! Old
bear!" making the reporter laugh.
</P>
<P>
After an Associated Press reporter took down from the wall
several pictures painted by the girl and asked her what they were
about, she answered clearly, "They are tadpoles looking for their
mummy."
</P>
<P>
During the tour, Shi Derong, director of the Shanghai Municipal
Civil Administration who is in charge of the institute's affairs,
Zhou Zhuqing, head of the Shanghai Child Welfare Institute, and
Han Weicheng, former head of the Shanghai Child Welfare Institute,
held a two-hour question and answer session with the reporters.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, they refuted lies that had been spread
by the New York-based Human Rights Watch/Asia. Shi said that the
Human Rights Watch/Asia report was said to have been compiled
on information and photos provided by Zhang Shuyun, a former
employee of the institute.
</P>
<P>
While working at the institute, Zhang was criticized for
violating rules of the institute. She lodged "complaints" against
Han Weicheng, the former head of the institute, and his superior,
with the slanderous accusation that Han had raped orphans, and
described the institute as a terrifying place.
</P>
<P>
After a long series of investigations, the Shanghai municipal
procuratorial body completely refuted the accusation of raping of
girl children and lies about the institute that accompanied the
accusation.
</P>
</TEXT>
