<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Child Welfare Institute, Home for Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Hang Zhuang, a nine-year-old
boy who is one of 500 orphans at the Shanghai Child Welfare
Institute, when asked, says, "I have a happy life here." .
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, 20 reporters from 19 media organizations in
Britain, France, the United States, and other Western countries,
along with several Chinese correspondents, visited the institute,
in downtown Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The director of the institute and doctors and nurses there
expressed the hope that the reporters would do an objective and
just job of reporting on this government-run charity organization.
</P>
<P>
This is Shanghai's only institute that cares for orphans who
have lost their parents as the result of natural disasters or
accidents, and for handicapped and severely mentally-retarded
children or those deserted by their parents.
</P>
<P>
It is home to some 500 orphans, mostly handicapped children, and
employs 320 people, including 42 doctors and nurses, 23 teachers,
and 220 child-care workers.
</P>
<P>
Director of the institute Zhou Zhuqing, said, "We follow a
principle of supporting, treating, and educating the children,"
and explains that support focuses on ensuring sufficient nutrition
for and care of the children. A nutritionist with the institute
has worked out a diet that is suited to the children's physical
conditons and ages, in order to help their healthy growth.
</P>
<P>
For treatment, the institute has inpatient facilities and a
child rehabilitation center, which treats illnesses or sends the
children to major hospitals in downtown Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, those children with disabilities have
rehabilitation help and orphans are given regular overall physical
check-ups.
</P>
<P>
These measures are intended to reduce the extent of deformity
of severely handicapped children and to enable
slightly-handicapped children to regain use of their limbs so that
they will be able to live and study as ordinary children in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, who is called "Mother Director" by the children, told
reporters: "You can go wherever you want to. All parts of the
institute are open to you."
</P>
<P>
The institute has five buildings with a total floor space of
17,000 sq m. There are row upon row of trees on the grounds which
can be viewed through the spotless windows.
</P>
<P>
In the Infant Ward on the second floor of the Red Building, the
director, Sheng Xiaowei, said that the children in his ward are
orphans under the age of four.
</P>
<P>
Most of them have congenital heart or brain diseases, Sheng
noted, explaining that they are cared for by 32 doctors and nurses
and are given rehabilitation exercises under the guidance of
child-care workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Bank To Be Formed In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's local Business
Women's Organization is raising one million US dollars to form a
bank for the benefit of women.
</P>
<P>
"We are still raising money, although we had hiccups at first
with the banks turning away those who wanted to make a donation
toward the exercise," said Jane Mutasa, president of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
The idea was borrowed from Bangladesh, where women there were
said to have been successfully running their own bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
