<HEADLINE> Fuel Price Hike Affects Transporters in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe road hauliers today
said the recent increase in petrol and diesel prices will add
another 2.8 million US dollars to annual fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
Transport Operators Association executive officer, Arther
Sandwith told the Zimbabwean National News Agency that it is most
likely transporters will pass on the costs to the consumers, and
many are already working out the new charges.
</P>
<P>
Fuel companies last week increased petrol and diesel prices by
just over 2.8 percent and 3.7 percent respectively, six months
after another increase in August last year following the
government budget.
</P>
<P>
He said although the fuel price hike might appear to be small,
it is, however, significant in terms of liters consumed.
</P>
<P>
Besides the increases in fuel prices, transport costs have
been rising drastically due to maintenance costs, toll fees and
labor, he added.
</P>
<P>
the rise in costs, he said, has faster than the economic
growth, reducing the operators profit margins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
