<HEADLINE> Drug Warlord's Army Surrenders in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The entire Mong Tai Army (MTA) of
drug warlord Khun Sa in the northeast of Myanmar has laid down its
arms and surrendered to the Myanmar government, the state-run
Radio Myanmar confirmed tonight.
</P>
<P>
The MTA in the Homong and Loilam areas in Shan state began
surrendering on January 5, said the radio report.
</P>
<P>
The official TV Myanmar also reported the surrender tonight
with footage of the scene.
</P>
<P>
The number of the surrendering MTA troops was reported to be
4,431 along with 3,483 pieces of weapons and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
No further details were available about Khun Sa himself and a
splinter group from the MTA.
</P>
<P>
A few days ago, Myanmar government troops advanced into Khun
Sa's Homong headquarters and occupied it without meeting any
resistance.
</P>
<P>
Between March and June last year, Myanmar government troops
launched two major offensives on Khun Sa's forces and captured 45
camps and three opium processing plants in eastern Shan state.
</P>
<P>
The offensives forced Khun Sa's army to withdraw from its main
strategic strongholds including the western part of Tachilek and
Mongkyut area, and cut two-thirds of its heroin production.
</P>
<P>
Last June, a split reportedly took place in Khun Sa's MTA,
which led to the resignation of Khun Sa from his posts in late
November.
</P>
<P>
Khun Sa, born in 1933 in Shan state, has been drug warlord
since the 1960s, controlling opium production in the golden
triangle where Laos, Myanmar and Thailand meet. He had later
fostered a 20,000-strong drug trafficking armed group.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested by the Myanmar government in 1969 but was
released after five years in exchange for two Russian doctors held
hostage by the drug warlord.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
