<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Invest Heavily in Afforestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 7.86 billion
yuan (947 million US dollars) in the third phase of the world's
largest afforestation project, Forestry Minister Xu Youfang said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Four million ha will be covered in 13 provinces and autonomous
regions in north, northwest and northeast China during the next
five years to improve the ecology and stop water loss, soil
erosion, and desertification," he said.
</P>
<P>
"About 26.7 million ha of farmland and 20 million ha of
grassland will be protected by forest belts as a result," he said,
adding that the proposed afforestation will contribute an
additional 13 million tons of grain and 7.5 million tons of grass
to the region each year.
</P>
<P>
Projected forest coverage rate for the 13 provinces and
autonomous regions is 10 percent, compared with 8.26 percent in
1995, Xu explained. Water loss and soil erosion on 250,000 sq km
and desertification of 100,000 sq km of the northern part of the
country will be treated.
</P>
<P>
Major shelter belts will be built in three provinces in
northeast China and in eight provinces and autonomous regions in
northwest and north China, including the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region and Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The major shelter belts are also to improve the ecology in and
around Beijing and Tianjin, two of the largest cities in China,
and to protect China's major corn-producing areas in the northeast
and to halt desertification in the Muus Desert in the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
China started construction work on a 4,480 km-long shelter belt
in 1978, known as the "Green Great Wall", in a move to combat
desertification and improve the ecology in 13 provinces and
autonomous regions, which accounts for 42 percent of the country's
total area.
</P>
<P>
The 72-year, eight-phase afforestation project (1978-2050), the
largest in the world, is also supposed to raise the forest
coverage rate for the 4.03 million sq km to 14.95 percent in 2050
from 5.05 percent in 1977.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
