<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Visits Flood-Stricken Areas in Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today visited the flood-stricken areas in Jakarta, where at least
five people were killed and thousands were forced to flee their
homes over the weekend in the worst flood hitting the capital in
the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Public Works Minister Radinal Moochtar,
Commander of the Jakarta Military Area Maj. Gen. Wiranto and
Jakarta Vice Governor M. Idroes, Soeharto went in a helicopter and
visited areas including Tanah Abang in central Jakarta, Kampung
Melayu and Cawang in east Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The president said that as a result of the flood, efforts
should be made to improve management of the Ciliwung river, one of
the 13 rivers running through the capital.
</P>
<P>
He urged people to help the government in combating the worst
flood in Jakarta since 1976.
</P>
<P>
The flood began pounding Jakarta last Wednesday, when
relentless torrential rains caused river banks to burst and swell
to dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
The floodgate indicator in Depok, 30 kilometers south of
Jakarta, showed that the Ciliwung river reached an unprecedented
level of 4.35 meters last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The water in the areas along the Ciliwung river in east,
central and south Jakarta rose to more than two meters high.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Jakartans were evacuated to nearby safe shelters
such as mosques, school buildings and government offices. The
sudden flood forced most of the people to leave their belongings
behind.
</P>
<P>
Millions of residents have been affected and tens of thousands
of people have sought emergency shelters.
</P>
<P>
In the flood-stricken areas, main roads were still inundated,
which caused serious traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta Governor Surjadi Soedirdja said Sunday that this year's
floods indicated that the conditions of the city's rivers are poor
and need to be improved.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Jakarta residents have a bad
habit of dumping wastes into the rivers, thus raising the level of
the river beds. The wastes also make it difficult for the river
water to flow into the sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
