<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Calls for Economic Cooperation Among SAARC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- India today asked the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) to enhance
substantially its regional trade and economic cooperation so as to
increase its bargaining strength in the post-Uruguay Round
scenario.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Indian Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao
when inaugurating a two-day SAARC trade and commerce ministers
conference here.
</P>
<P>
This has become imperative with changes in recent years which
include dwindling development assistance from the developed world,
greater integration of world economies and attempted
neo-protectionist linkages with considerations like human rights,
labor standards and environment, Rao said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his serious concern over the SAARC
countries' share in the total world trade which was even less than
one percent. Trade among SAARC nations themselves also lingered
below three percent of their total foreign trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
This compares poorly with 63.4 percent for intra-European Union
trade of its global trade in 1990, 37.3 percent for North America,
and 38.4 percent for Southeast Asia, Rao said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his satisfaction that the process of substantial
regional economic cooperation had already begun, Rao said there
was ample evidence of a general willingness in all SAARC countries
to import from their neighbors and buy their goods.
</P>
<P>
This should impel the member states to adopt the appropriate
policy measures for promotion and facilitation of trade with one
another, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, founded in December 1985, comprises India, Pakistan,
Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan and the Maldives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres Optimistic over Peace Talks with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Shimon Peres
said today that a "promising beginning" has been achieved in the
peace negotiations between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Peres made the comment when he was addressing an annual
luncheon of the Foreign Press Association.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether he is optimistic over the peace process
with Syria, he replied that he would lose his job if he stops
being optimistic.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister declined to say whether Israel will
have a complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights as Syria has
demanded.
</P>
<P>
He explained that he is optimistic because over the past more
or less two months, the Syrian media gave very positive reaction
to Israel's good will in searching for ways to restart the stalled
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Peres noted that the latest round of talks in Maryland, the
United States had created an atmosphere and climate which are
needed for serious negotiations. Mutual trust should come ahead of
concrete plans, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday evening, Peres was briefed by members of the Israeli
delegation, who returned for consultations after the six-day new
round of talks in Wye River conference center, Maryland, some 70
miles outside Washington, in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher is expected to
conduct a shuttle diplomacy between Syria and Israel this week,
apparently designed to secure more substantial results. New rounds
of Syrian-Israeli talks will follow.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. role in a possible future peace
agreement, Peres said he would not ask American soldiers to defend
Israel, but ask for a U.N. observer team, with U.S. participation,
to station on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the forthcoming Palestinian elections, Peres said
he hopes it will be democratic, but he expressed his
understanding of PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's difficulties in the
democratic experiment.
</P>
<P>
Peres dismissed a suggestion that the killing of Yihye Ayyash,
a noted Activist of the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas),
would make Arafat feel uncomfortable, saying that it is Hamas
and Islamic Jihad which will feel uncomfortable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
