<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial: China Striving For Good Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A conference on rural work held
by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) has
worked out basic plans for developing the rural economy in line
with the goals of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), according
to an editorial by the People's Daily to be published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It will play a positive role in mobilizing the Chinese people
to work hard for a bumper harvest and creating new conditions in
rural areas this year.
</P>
<P>
The editorial, entitled "Striving For A Bumper Harvest This
Year", says that a good harvest will not only ensure an adequate
supply of farm products, but will also increase farmers' income
and curb inflation, and will lay a solid foundation for developing
agriculture to reach the goals of the Ninth Five-Year Plan.
</P>
<P>
It is important to put agriculture first in developing national
economy. Officials at various government levels should give
priority to agricultural production when making work plans or
allocating funds. They should devote most of their energy and
efforts to agriculture and rural work, says the editorial.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels should especially be certain that
demands in agriculture for funding and increasing of finances, and
for capital construction and loans are met. It is also necessary
that new channels for investment in agriculture be opened up.
</P>
<P>
Resolute checks should be made on the misuse of land, and the
diverting of funds, materials, and talented personnel to other
uses.
</P>
<P>
The editorial points out that China often suffers from natural
disasters, so it is important that water conservancy projects be
carried out nationwide on large scale in order to defend against
disasters better, as a means of guaranteeing good, stable yields.
</P>
<P>
While big rivers are being harnessed, more attention should
also be paid to building small water conservancy projects as well.
</P>
<P>
In order to have a good harvest this year, efforts should also
be made to popularize scientific achievements and apply them to
grain production and development of cash products.
</P>
<P>
To meet the goal, the editorial says, it is necessary to
improve leadership in agriculture and in rural work while giving
full play to farmers' initiative. And more attention should also
be paid to easing farmers' burdens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
