<HEADLINE> Pakistan Compensates Victims of Karachi Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government today
gave each family of the eight people killed in a bus bomb blast
100,000 rupees (2,900 US dollars) in compensation, local press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb exploded in an overcrowded bus in the southern port
city of Karachi on Sunday at the rush hour of 6:00 PM, killing
eight people and injuring another 28.
</P>
<P>
The advisor to the Sindh provincial chief minister, Munawwar
Suharwardy, also announced that each of the 28 injured in the
blast will get 30,000 rupees (876 US dollars) as compensation.
</P>
<P>
Suharwardy handed over the compensation cheques while visiting
the injured at a local hospital in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
He assured them that the government will bear the expenses of
treatment of the four victims whose limbs were amputated at the
hospital to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the bomb blast was the work of "anti-state
elements" and that the culprits will not be allowed to go
unpunished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
