<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Willing to Join Peace Monitors on Golan Heights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Perry said here today that Washington will be willing to
participate in a peace monitoring force on the Golan Heights if
Israel and Syria reach a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Perry made the statement after meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Shimon Peres, who also holds the post of defense
minister, in Jerusalem this morning.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the Golan Heights from Syria during the 1967
Middle East war, and the Knesset (Israel's parliament) passed a
law in 1981 to annex the heights.
</P>
<P>
At the previous peace negotiations with Israel, Syria said
that Israel must fully withdraw from the Golan Heights before any
peace agreement could be reached between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel insisted on full normalization of relations and
security arrangements as a priority, saying that the depth of
withdrawal would reflect the depth of peace.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Peres, Perry also announced that
the U.S. will provide Israel with 200 million U.S. dollars over
the next five years to help fund the 500-million-dollar Arrow
Anti-Missile project.
</P>
<P>
Perry arrived here this morning from Amman, capital of Jordan,
as part of a Middle East tour, which also took him to Saudi
Arabia and Oman, and is scheduled to leave Israel later today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher will
arrive in the region on Wednesday at the start of a new round of
shuttle between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
During his 16th visit to the Middle East, Christopher will
discuss with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and Israeli Prime
Minister Peres about the results of the Israeli-Syrian
negotiations held in the U.S. over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria held two rounds of talks in Wye River
conference center, Maryland, and both sides said that there was a
warmer atmosphere in the negotiations, though no agreements had
been reached so far.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that Christopher's visit will likely
lead to further negotiations between Israel and Syria at the end
of this month, aimed at pushing forward the peace process between
the two countries. 
</P>
