<HEADLINE> World Food Program Brings Food Relief to Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
has brought more than 2,000 tons of wheat and flour to Kabul,
capital of Afghanistan, in relief supplies to the country, reports
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted WFP officials as saying today that the food
brought by a truck convoy arranged by WFP arrived in the besieged
Kabul Saturday.
</P>
<P>
UN officials earlier warned that without additional relief
supplies, some one million Kabul residents could face starvation
with the onset of winter's bitter weather.
</P>
<P>
The consignment will be used in about 100 WFP-subsidized
bakeries to produce bread for around 170,000 Kabulis, they said.
</P>
<P>
The WFP is also arranging food and medical supplies for
hospital patients, children and orphans, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The agency also plans to start bringing more than 1,000 tons of
wheat and flour per week in the near future.
</P>
<P>
This was the single largest delivery of supplies into Kabul,
which has been isolated by the Taliban student militia since last
October.
</P>
<P>
All but one routes leading to Kabul have been cut off by the
rivals of Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani. The rivals are
demanding that Rabbani step down and an interim neutral government
be set up.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
