<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Pays Tribute to Mitterrand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
today paid glowing tribute to what he called the outstanding
achievements of former French President Francois Mitterrand, who
died earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand made an "outstanding contribution to public life
throughout the post-war period and he would be remembered long
after his death," Major was quoted by BBC television as saying.
</P>
<P>
"He faced very serious illness with exceptional courage and
dignity" and he will be mourned by friends and admirers around the
world, Major added.
</P>
<P>
Major's predecessor, Margaret Thatcher, has also reportedly
praised Mitterrand, saying she "liked and respected" him although
she held different political views from the late president who was
a life-long Socialist.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand, who stepped down as president last May, had been
suffering from prostate cancer and died this morning at the age of
79. He came to power in 1981 and won a second seven-year term in
1988. 
</P>
