<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Treasury Uneasy over Sacking of Stock Exchange Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- British Treasury ministers have
expressed uneasiness over the sacking of Michael Lawrence, chief
executive of the London Stock Exchange (LSE), and concern that the
resulting upheaval will slow the pace of change in the market.
</P>
<P>
Both ministers and civil servants were reportedly uneasy at the
timing and manner of Lawrence's dismissal last week and the
implications for trading and other reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury is believed to have been taken by surprise by
Lawrence's abrupt departure and is hoping that Ian Plenderleith,
the Bank of England executive director and the LSE's new joint
deputy chairman, will maintain the pressure for change.
</P>
<P>
One Whitehall source said "the question is whether the Stock
Exchange is going to get on with the changes he (Lawrence) had in
mind or whether the forces of darkness will play them into the
long grass".
</P>
<P>
The Treasury is also said to be furious at speculation that it
was involved in seeking Lawrence's dismissal because of an
"insider-trading" row over last year's sale of shares in
electricity generators National Power and PowerGen.
</P>
<P>
The Exchange will try to find a replacement for Lawrence this
week and publish a consultation document on the new trading system
due to start in August.
</P>
<P>
Reforms to create an order-driven, fully electronic share
trading system was one of Lawrence's priorities but he was
criticized for trying to drive reform too hard with too little
consultation.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence, 52, became the LSE's chief executive in February
1994. He was forced to resign last Thursday after "a loss of
confidence in him".
</P>
<P>
John Kemp-Welch, chairman of the LSE, denied Lawrence was a
scapegoat for controversies last year, including the move toward
order-driven trading which met strong opposition from LSE members
and was described by a senior executive as the real reason behind
Lawrence's departure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
