<HEADLINE> Thai Rubber Exports May Benefit From Tariff Cut in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand, one of the world's
largest rubber producers and exporters, may benefit from China's
planned tariff cut on rubber imports, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to slash tariffs on rubber imports this year.
</P>
<P>
Rubber prices in Thailand would remain over 30 baht (1.2
U.S. dollars) per kilogram until March, the Agriculture
Department's Rubber Research Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government guarantees a rubber price of 25 baht (1
dollar) per kilogram and intervenes if the price slips below
that.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the rubber market in Thailand remains healthy
despite traditionally sluggish trade in December and January every
year and the rubber price is still at 35 baht (1.4 dollars) per
kilogram, the institute noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
