<HEADLINE> Pakistan Price Index Declines to 9.8 Percent in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The sensitive price index in
Pakistan declined to 9.8 percent in 1995 as compared to 17.5
percent in 1994, said Information Minister Khalid Kharal here
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, the minister said that decline in
the prices of kitchen items has been more pronounced to 7 percent
in December 1995 compared with that of 21.5 percent in December
1994.
</P>
<P>
He said that a significant decline in the prices of potatoes,
onions, tomatoes and garlic has been witnessed.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that deceleration in inflation is providing more
relief to low-income consumers.
</P>
<P>
According to the government's budget for the fiscal year from
July 1995 to June 1996, inflation is expected to stay within 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
An average of 15.6 percent increase was observed in the last
three years in prices of 19 kitchen items, including wheat flour,
rice, mutton, beef, edible oil, potatoes, tomatoes, chillies and
garlic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
