<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Treasure-Hunters to Quit Digging for Gold Bars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A Thai official said today that
excavators would stop their search Tuesday for treasures and gold
bars believed to be left behind by Japanese soldiers during World
War II in west Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Intensive digging in the past three weeks in a forest in
Kanchanaburi province, west Thailand, has unearthed nothing of any
significant value.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Education Minister Chaovarin Latthasaksiri, who had all
along supported the digging, told reporters today that if there
was still no sign of gold, he would withdraw his support.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Chaovarin's secretary told reporters that the deputy
minister had been shown "irrefutable proofs" of the existence of
the treasures in the province by the manager of a fortune-hunting
company.
</P>
<P>
In the course of the digging, police have arrested several
fortune-hunters on charges of damaging forest reserves.
</P>
<P>
In World War II, Japanese aggressor troops made allied
prisoners of war and Asian laborers build a railway, now known as
"the death railway," in Kanchanaburi to link up Siam (Thailand)
with Burma (Myanmar) to transport war materials at the expense of
thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
Rumors surface from time to time that Japanese soldiers buried
their booty in the forest at the time of their withdrawal, in the
hope that they could come back to claim it later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
