<HEADLINE> Central Rural Conference Outlines Major Tasks for 1996-2000 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A conference on rural work held
by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
closed here today, calling on the whole country to strive for the
goal set in the country's Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The three-and-half-day conference placed its emphasis on some
major issues on agricultural development in the Ninth Five-Year
Plan.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, senior party leaders Jiang Zemin, Li
Peng, Li Ruihuan, Zhu Rongji, Liu Huaqing and Hu jintao have met
with participants.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central Committee,
urged participants to work hard for reaping a bumper harvest this
year and contribute more to economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chunyun, member of the CPC Central Committee's Political
Bureau and vice premier, delivered a keynote speech at the
conference which was presided over by Wen Jiabao, an alternate
member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and
secretariat of the Central Committee. State Councillor Chen
Junsheng made a summary speech.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Jilin, Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Shandong,
Guangdong, Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces and of some government
departments also spoke at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The general demand for the development of agriculture and rural
affairs in 1996, the conference held, is to implement the goals
set by the Fifth Plenum of the 14th Central Committee and the
Central Economic Work Conference, put agriculture in the first
place of the national economy, carry out the party's rural
policies, deepen economic reforms in rural areas, build a new
mechanism and work out new measures to cope with problems that
cropped up in rural economic development.
</P>
<P>
As 1996 is the first year of China's Ninth Five-Year Plan, the
conference called for redoubled efforts to gain a good
agricultural harvest, thus laying a good foundation for the Ninth
Five-Year Plan.
</P>
<P>
The conference outlined eight major issues to be tackled in
rural economic development during the 1996-2000 period:
</P>
<P>
-- Give priority to agriculture in terms of fund allocations;
</P>
<P>
-- Solve problems of common concern by farmers and protecting
and giving scope to their initiative;
</P>
<P>
-- Raise comprehensive production capacity of agriculture which
includes farmland capital construction, improvement of medium-and
low-yield fields, development of agriculture-related industry and
upgrading of storage and transport facilities;
</P>
<P>
-- Implement the strategy of invigorating agriculture through
science and education and enhance high-tech development for
agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
