<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Official Urges Development of Legal Science Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior official today urged
the country's law workers to step up reforms to promote legal
science education with the cultivation of a large number of
capable personnel well versed in the law.
</P>
<P>
"Being an important component of the national education system,
legal science education must be boosted at a faster speed to
contribute to the establishment of a modern socialist nation with
a sound legal system," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, a member of the secretariat of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee and secretary of the Political
Science and Law Committee under the CPC Central Committee, made
the remarks at a national conference on legal science education
which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is China's first national one since the
country's law-enforcement departments were restored in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"The shift from the traditional planned economy to a socialist
market economy makes it imperative that the country be managed in
accordance with the law," Ren said, adding that legal personnel
are badly needed in judicial, legislative and executive
departments, and institutions specializing in legal services and
supervision.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the Ministry of Justice, China has
formed a legal science education system connected with university
and college schooling, adult education and occupational training.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 16 years, some 160 higher-learning institutions
or departments of legal science education have been set up or
restored across the country. Besides, there are 29 correspondence
centers and 200 sub-centers for providing knowledge of the law.
</P>
<P>
However, statistics show that by the end of 1994 Chinese
university and college students studying legal science accounted
for only 2.2 percent of all students. Among current lawyers, 25
percent have a bachelor's degree and only 1.49 percent hold a
master's degree.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, minister of Justice, said today that in the coming
years legal science education in China should be expanded to a
larger scale in order to meet the needs of the socialist market
economy, democratic legal construction and overall social
progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Semiconductor Market Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The semiconductor market in
the Asia-Pacific region expanded by a strong 41 percent last year,
with the manufacturers overtaking their American and European
counterparts in terms of revenue growth, according to industrial
sources here today.
</P>
<P>
They said that the total revenue for the year was 33.5 billion
US dollars, while the region increased its share of world-wide
consumption to a best-ever 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from research group Dataquest Inc., the sources
noted that what was particularly impressive was the performance of
companies originating from the Asia-Pacific, excluding those from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
World-wide revenues of these companies, especially the
manufacturers of the Dynamic Random Access Memory from South
Korea, grew by a sizzling 84.2 percent, they said.
</P>
<P>
This was more than double the average revenue growth rates of
companies from North America, Japan, and Europe respectively, they
said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the figures helped confirm the Asia-Pacific's
position as the most dynamic region for semiconductor production
and consumption world-wide.
</P>
<P>
North American semiconductor companies registered a revenue
growth of 36.6 percent in the 1994-95 period, while Japanese
companies recorded a revenue growth of 37. 6 percent, and European
companies, 35.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The world-wide share of Asia-Pacific semiconductor companies
has risen from under 4 percent in 1990 to 6 percent in 1992, and
to 12 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
North American and Japanese companies still dominate the market
with about 40 percent each, though the Japanese have seen their
market share shrinking steadily from 46 percent in 1990, while the
American share came down from 43 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
European companies have suffered most in terms of the market
share, as theirs has fallen from 11.2 percent in 1990 to 8.6
percent last year, the sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
