<HEADLINE> China Donates Relief Goods to Afghan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China today donated relief
goods worth 3.5 million yuan (about 420,000 US dollars) to the
repatriated Afghan refugees, a Chinese diplomat said at a
handing-over ceremony here.
</P>
<P>
Fu Guangting, the Economic and Commercial Counselor of the
Chinese embassy in Pakistan, said that the donation, composed of
medicines, woolen blankets, tea and fire extinguishers, should be
transferred to Afghan people as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government and people are deeply concerned over
the situation in Afghanistan and the plight of the refugees and
the displaced persons in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope for the early realization of
Afghanistan's reconciliation, which, he said, would contribute to
the resettlement of the refugees and the reconstruction of the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The donation was made under the Notes exchanged on June 28 and
August 10, 1995, between the Chinese government and the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Anoushiravan Daneshvar, deputy chief of the UNHCR Mission for
Afghanistan, said at the ceremony that the Chinese relief goods
already arrived in Peshawar, Pakistan, and were received and
checked by the UNHCR Peshawar office.
</P>
<P>
Daneshvar said that China was the only donor that aided Afghan
refugees in kind since the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current donation would mainly be used in the
Jalalabad area of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan and Iran had received altogether about
six million Afghan refugees during the Afghan war.
</P>
<P>
"Presently, about 65 percent of the refugees have been
repatriated," he said.
</P>
<P>
On December 24, 1995, China donated relief goods worth 1.5
million yuan (about 180,000 US dollars) to Afghan refugees
residing in Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
