<HEADLINE> Former French President Mitterrand dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Former French President Francois
Mitterrand died today, at the age of 79, his office confirmed.
</P>
<P>
"The president died this morning at 8.30 a.m.," his personal
secretariat said. Mitterrand died nearly eight month after
completing a record 14 years as head of state.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand's conservative successor President Jacques Chirac,
meeting the press at the Elysee Palace, confirmed the death.
</P>
<P>
The former French president, who had been suffering from
prostate cancer, swept to power in 1981. He won re-election for a
second seven-year term in 1988.
</P>
<P>
He turned the Socialist Party into an enduring government
force, becoming France's longest-serving president.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand was born on October 26, 1916, in the historic town
of Jarnac in the Charente department of western France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
