<HEADLINE> Singapore's Share Prices Continue to Surge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- After last week's rally, share
prices continued to surge higher on the Singapore market, as the
benchmark Straits Times Industrials (STI) index picked up by
another 20.34 points to close at 2,385.87 today.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was 354.12 million units, valued at
718.8 million Singapore dollars (some 502.66 million US dollars).
Rises overwhelmed falls by 336 to 50, while 137 other counters
remained steady from last week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the local market was expected to stay
firm this week although the powerful New Year rally could be
checked by sporadic profit-taking. They said that the STI index
could reach the 2400 level this week.
</P>
<P>
The STI index gained almost 100 points last week, as foreign
fund managers returned from holidays to buy up stocks against the
backdrop of strong economic fundamentals of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Berjaya Group was the most actively traded counter, chalking up
a turnover of 12.82 million units. MCB was next with 9.68 million
of its shares traded, while IPC saw 8.88 million of its shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
MCB led the gainers of the day, as it put on 68 cents to 1.77
Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) Foreign gained
50 cents to 26.4 Singapore dollars, while UMW picked up by 36
cents to 4.28 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Bukit Sembawang, Jurong Shipyard, and MAA each
lost 40 cents to 30.5, 11, and 6.3 Singapore dollars respectively.
 City Development and the Keppel Corporation each shed 30 cents to
11 and 12.8 Singapore dollars respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
