<HEADLINE> Two Malaysian Districts Declared Rabies Control Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Kuala Terengganu and Marang
in Malaysia's Terengganu state have been declared rabies control
areas by the country's veterinary authorities, the Bernama news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bernama quoted Ibrahim Embong, an official at the veterinary
services department, as saying that the move was taken after some
residents in both districts were attacked by dogs feared to be
rabid.
</P>
<P>
The gazette notification, which was signed today, would allow
the department to take steps to destroy stray dogs in both
districts.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim said the cause of the disease could not be confirmed,
but he believed the rabies virus could have originated from dogs
used in wild boar hunts.
</P>
<P>
The disease could be spread among the population if it was not
checked, Ibrahim said, adding that one case had been detected in
Kuala Terengganu after a housewife was bitten by a dog last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, three children in Marang were admitted to hospital
after being bitten by a rabid dog, Bernama said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
