<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Latest Cabinet Reshuffle Planned since Last Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
revealed that he had planned the latest cabinet reshuffle since
last summer.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Mayo, mouthpiece of the ruling National
Democratic Party (NDP), Mubarak said that he had been tight-lipped
about the plan lest "the national course of action should be
negatively affected."
</P>
<P>
The interview was published today in the weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet shift is aimed at streamlining Egypt's political
life and coping with world developments, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak appointed Kamal el-Ganzouri as the prime minister to
form a new cabinet last Tuesday following the resignation of
former Prime Minister Atef Sedki's government.
</P>
<P>
The move came as a surprise since Mubarak had said after the
parliamentary elections last month that he saw no need for major
cabinet changes.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle is believed to have been aimed at quickening the
pace of the country's faltering economic reform and reshaping the
image of the government, which has been accused by opposition
parties of widespread vote rigging in the parliamentary elections,
in which the NDP claimed a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
Three portfolios related to economy -- finance, economy and
industry -- changed hands, further indicating that the new
government would aim to achieve more rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, who also serves as the planning minister, said
Saturday at a cabinet meeting that the new government would try to
double the current economic growth rate to exceed that of the
population growth, create job opportunities, increase exports and
attract more investments in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Mubarak also said that a large-scale
reshuffle of provincial governors will be announced in the second
half of this month.
</P>
<P>
He added that an assessment of the performance of governors is
currently underway.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, however, said that there will be no changes in the
leadership of the NDP at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
