<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comprehensive and Just Peace Means Ending Israeli Occupation: Hrawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
called here today for an Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon,
saying this is demanded by U.N. Security Council resolution 425
and enjoined by a comprehensive and just peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
At an annual new year reception of foreign ambassadors and
envoys in Lebanon in the Presidential Palace, the Lebanese
president announced that his country is on the road of a
"honorable" peace and is seeking an end of the Israeli occupation
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the road of a honorable peace," the President said.
"We want to end the Israeli occupation in the south and Western
Bekaa till we regain our right on territory and sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
"This is provided for by the resolution 425, and this is what a
comprehensive and just peace means," Hrawi stressed in his speech.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country is against any peace settlement which
is at the expense of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi reiterated a Lebanese promise that it will guarantee
security on the border with Israel once the Jewish state pulls its
forces out of the occupied strip in the south, which is
self-proclaimed by Israel as the "security zone."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized a special relationship with Syria which is based
on "understanding, cooperation and coordination."
</P>
<P>
He also underlined inseparability of the Lebanese and Syrian
tracks of peace talks with Israel, pointing out that coordination
of the two tracks is "our firm decision and a guarantee for the
realization of a comprehensive and just peace."
</P>
<P>
Hrawi repeated Lebanon's refusal to resettle Palestinian
refugees in this country. "Our constitution stipulates 'no
resettlement,'" and all the Lebanese refuse the resettlement, the
president said, adding that the Palestinian refugees in Lebanon
also want to return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
He called for an early release of Lebanese prisoners jailed by
Israel, and a dismantle of all mass-destruction weapons in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese president urged the United States to lift a
travel ban on the American citizens to Lebanon, thus to reopen the
airways between the two countries and to enable "American
airliners to land at our airport and Lebanese airliners to land at
American airports."
</P>
<P>
The travel ban was imposed by the U.S. administration
following a series of attacks against American interests in Beirut
in the middle of the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
