<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien Goes to Asia to Open New Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 8 (xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien is heading for Asia today on an 11-day trade mission to
India, Pakistan, Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
It is his second visit to Asia since November 1994 when he
visited China and other Asian countries and regions. During that
trip the Canadian delegation signed with China 8.6 billion
Canadian dollars (some 6.3 billion U.S. dollars) worth of
contracts, memorandums and letters of intent.
</P>
<P>
Chretien will try a "Team Canada" approach to trade promotion
this time as he did in China a year ago. Seven provincial premiers
and more than 300 businessmen will accompany him in the visit.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to sign at least 2 billion Canadian dollars
(some 1.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of agreements on
telecommunications, transportation, energy and environmental and
financial services, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Among the four countries which have a total population of 1.15
billion and great trade potentials, Indonesia is Canada's largest
export market, which imported 475 million Canadian dollars (about
351.5 million U.S. dollars) worth of goods and services from
Canada in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Canada's trade volume with Malaysia hit 1.5 billion Canadian
dollars (some 1.1 billion U.S. dollars) in 1994 but Canadian
exports to the country accounted for only 291.5 million dollars
(about 215.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Canada's exports to India totaled 316 million Canadian
dollars (some 233.8 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of
1995. Its investments in India reached 151 million Canadian
dollars (about 111.7 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of
last year, an eightfold increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of bilateral trade between Canada and Pakistan
is relatively small. But a certain number of Canadian companies
are being involved in projects such as power projects and
rapid-transit system in Karachi worth billions of Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Canadian Minister for International Trade Roy
MacLaren, the Asia-Pacific region will play an important role in
the economic future of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Chretien's Asian visit will bear a great significance since
Canada's economic growth slowed in 1995 due to high interest
rates, consumers' low confidence and feeble domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Canada is expected to achieve more than 2.2 percent of
economic growth in 1995 and its exceptional performance in
foreign markets is believed to have played an important role in
the growth.
</P>
<P>
The visit is also seen as a government effort to reestablish
its focus on economic development and job creation rather than on
national unity. The October-30 referendum on Quebec separation
last year turned public attention to national unity and had a
negative impact on the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
