<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres: Syria Agrees on Principle of Peace with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres said here Sunday night that Syria has agreed that peace
between Israel and the rest of the Arab countries should be the
aim of the current negotiations between Israel and Syria,
according to local media reports today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Israel Bond Rabbis Conference in Jerusalem,
Peres said that there was a warmer atmosphere in the peace
negotiations with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
"In our judgment," said Peres, "the Syrians accepted the
principle to see a possible peace agreement with Israel has an
attempt to make it a comprehensive peace between Israel and the
rest of the Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Israeli-Syrian negotiations held in
the U.S. over the past weeks had been conducted in "a different
opening" and "more informal" way.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Peres was briefed by the Israeli negotiation team on
the two rounds of negotiations between Israel and Syria held in
Maryland, the U.S., during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli negotiation team, headed by Uri Savir,
director-general of the foreign ministry and peace process
coordinator, returned from the U.S. to Israel Sunday afternoon to
report to Peres and the government on the results of the talks
with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria resumed their peace negotiations on December
27 last year, and talks were held at the Wye River Conference
Center in Maryland, as an effort to avoid press disturbing.
</P>
<P>
The first three days of talks ended on December 29, and the two
sides agreed to an American suggestion that they remain in the
U.S. during the long New Year weekend to continue informal
contacts.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who is scheduled to
arrive in the region Wednesday for another diplomatic shuttle
between Israel and Syria, joined with the Israeli and Syrian
negotiators in the second three days of talks which started last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media said that Christopher's visit will likely lead
to further Israeli-Syrian negotiations at the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
