<HEADLINE> Ugandan Troops Open Fire On Sudan Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan People's Defense
Force (UPDF) has twice opened fire on Sudanese bombers after they
violated Ugandan territory, the local newspaper "the Monitor"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Edison Muzoora, the UPDF Brigade Commander based in Kitgum in
northern Uganda, was quoted as saying that the UPDF had on two
separate occasions last month shot at Sudanese planes after they
flew into Uganda air space, but missed the planes.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that Sudanese bombers constantly flew
overhead the border villages in Uganda almost throughout December
last year.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Uganda and the Sudan have been bumpy since
1986. They charge each other for supporting the anti-government
forces of its own country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda severed diplomatic relations with the Sudan on April 23
last year. 
</P>
