<HEADLINE> Certificates a Must for Peasants to Contract Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- In the countryside of the
Pudong New Area of this, China's biggest city a new regulation
stipulates that without a special certificate, peasants are not
allowed to contract fields.
</P>
<P>
The certificate is offered by the regional agricultural organs
to peasants who have finished a three-month training course.
</P>
<P>
The training course offers five subjects: basic agriculture,
modern agriculture, marketing, economic policy and professional
ethics.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fuyao, a farmer from east China's Zhejiang Province, has
applied to the Tangzhen Village authorities to contract 30 ha of
land next year, attributing his confidence to the knowledge he
learned in the training course.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Genchu, deputy head of the village, said, "The Pudong New
Area will not only be developed into a modern city, but also one
with modern agriculture. We are making efforts to let every
peasant know that experience alone is far from enough to be a
modern farmer."
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the new regulation has proved to be feasible
and has received a positive response from the peasants. To date,
more than 20 peasants have applied for the next training course,
which is scheduled to start soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
