<HEADLINE> Turkish FM Accuses Syria of Sheltering Rebel PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Deniz
Baykal accused Syria of "harboring terrorists," who often
infiltrate into the Turkish territories to attack various targets,
the local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Baykal said during a program on Interstar TV that "this should
be said clearly and I am doing so, in my role as foreign minister,
the headquarters of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) is in
Damascus."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister made the remarks in response to
the escalating tensions in Turco-Syrian ties on the water issue.
</P>
<P>
"How can you reconcile this with good neighborliness? how can
you keep the head of a terrorist organization in your capital?"
Baykal asked.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting in southeastern Turkey for
independence since 1984 and about 20,000 people have been killed
in the clashes between the PKK rebels and Turkish government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Baykal added that the Syrian policy was unacceptable and had to
be changed.
</P>
<P>
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan is believed to be living in
Damascus. Although the Syrians publicly deny this, two German
officials who wanted to talk to Ocalan met him in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Ankara, irked by the meetings, divided its rage between
Germany and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister also denied that Turkey had ever
deprived Syria of water and invited both Syria and Iraq to discuss
Turkey's three-stage plan to work out an equitable allocation of
water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
