<HEADLINE> Expert Team Begins Aerial Survey in Indian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A three-member expert team
today commenced its aerial survey in two helicopters to study the
water level and crop status in Cauvery basin districts in
Karnataka State, the Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The team was set up by Prime Minister P. V. Narasimha Rao as
part of his efforts to settle the Cauvery water dispute between
Karnataka and Tamil Nadu states. The team had already finished its
survey in Tamil Nadu and will submit its report after completing
its survey in Karnataka state.
</P>
<P>
Official sources in Bangalore, state capital of Karnataka, said
the team would visit parts of Mandya, the heartland of Cauvery
basin, and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
The neighboring Karnataka and Tamil Nadu have recently been
locked in a dispute over whether Karnataka should release 11
thousand million cubic (TMC) feet of Cauvery water to save
standing crops in Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
Karnataka finally agreed to release 6 TMC feet of water to
Tamil Nadu in deference to a directive announced by the prime
minister on January 2 but still insisted that Tamil Nadu has
enough water itself to meet the need of crops in the state.
</P>
