<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 07:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Urges Control Over Local Money Appreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- An analytical report by the
State Administration of Foreign Exchange Control (SAFEC) proposes
that the government take measures to ensure that the local
currency, the yuan, does not appreciate by a big margin over the
US dollar for a relatively long time.
</P>
<P>
One way is to effectively contain price rises so that the
exchange rate can remain basically stable to support the
competitiveness of the country's exports, said the report on the
movement of the RMB exchange rate in 1996 carried in the "Shanghai
Securities News" today.
</P>
<P>
Despite the surge in the yuan's value over the dollar in the
past year the local money lost ground over other hard currencies
in general as the yuan's appreciation rate over the US dollar was
lower than over the other currencies, noted the report.
</P>
<P>
But the high inflation last year counteracted to some extent
the effect of the cheaper yuan's export competitiveness, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
However, it predicted that the yuan exchange rate would remain
relatively stable as "a big gap in foreign exchange demand and
supply is unlikely to occur during the first half of this year."
</P>
<P>
The report said factors determining the movement of the yuan's
exchange rate are rather complicated. Those to the advantage of a
stable yuan include a well-placed tight monetary and credit
policy, relatively high interest rates, an expected high inflow
of foreign capital and further expansion of exports.
</P>
<P>
But continued inflation, price rises and a reduction of export
tax rebates could weaken the export growth momentum this year,
noted the report, adding that expansion in fixed assets investment
could lead to an increase in imports.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of foreign capital might slow down with the gradual
recovery of the Western economies, and China has entered a peak
period of foreign debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
All these factors might combine together to pull down the
yuan's exchange rate, cautioned the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
