<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's mainstream opposition
parties started their 48-hour nationwide strike today to further
demonstrate their demand for the resignation of Prime Minister
Begum Khaleda Zia and the setting up of a neutral caretaker
government to hold the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
The three mainstream opposition parties -- the Awami (people's)
League, the Jatiya (national) Party and the Jamaat-e-Islami --
earlier announced the strike program for January 3-4, but later
shifted the date to January 8-9 after the Election Commission set
January 8 as the last date for filing nomination papers for the
February 7 national elections.
</P>
<P>
To drum up support for the strike, the opposition parties last
night held rallies and torch processions in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Sheikh Hasina, former opposition leader in the
parliament and president of the Awami League warned that people
would resist at any cost the government's "farce in the name of
election" without the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) government's lust
for power was pushing the country towards constitutional crisis,
Hasina said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, senior ministers had a two-hour meeting with the
prime minister last night to discuss the political situation in
the country.
BNP Secretary General Barrister Abdus Salam Talukder briefed them
on the negotiation with the oppositions and proposals put forward
by the opposition side, but no concrete decision to resolve the
current crisis was taken at the meeting, sources said.  
</P>
