<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sale of Iodized Salt Inquired in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has formed a special
committee to inquire into the sale of iodized salt in order to
check the severe condition of iodine deficiency in this Himalayan
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
A sub-committee formed under the Public Accounts Committee of
the House of Representatives met Sunday and decided to ask the
state-owned Salt Trading Corporation to submit a report on its
salt sales within a week.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that thousands of Nepalese children were
suffering from mentally retarded life due to the government's
inability to supply iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
The iodine deficiency disorder (IDD) could also lead
miscarriage, stillbirth and cretinism which are widespread
especially in the country's remote mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that intake of iodized salt worth two rupees
(less than four US cents) every year for one person could prevent
the IDD disease.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese government started an anti-IDD program two decades
ago but critics said that the situation had barely improved since
then.
</P>
<P>
Lack of awareness among rural people and the negligence of
government officials were blamed as main reasons for the
prevalence of IDD in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the recently ended house session, legislators asked the
government to provide one kilogram of iodized salt to each family.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
and the World Health Organization (WHO) in Nepal urged the
lawmakers to initiate a bill to prohibit the marketing of
iodineless salt.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the government-run Salt Trading
Corporation, the company has already stopped importing iodineless
salt but it is being imported illegally due to the habit to use
crystalline salt among rural people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
