<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 06:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Political Parties Forge Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil political
parties are forging a consensus so that they can take a joint
Tamil position before the Parliamentary Select Committee which
will discuss the legal draft of the government's devolution
package, a Tamil political source said today.
</P>
<P>
"We have met a few times and reached a common position. We will
talk with the others so that we can place a joint Tamil position,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, all Tamil Parties approved a four-point program
calling for a merged northeast province, full autonomy, and for a
Muslim unit within the province and Sinhalese in the northeast to
enjoy rights similar to those enjoyed by Tamils and Muslims
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil parties now want to include three more points. These
are a secular state, citizenship for all who live in Sri Lanka for
ten years and the alteration of the phrase "Union of Regions" to
"Union of States" in the draft of the devolution package.
</P>
<P>
The devolution package announced by the government in August
aims to resolve the long-standing ethnic crisis in the country. It
contains proposals for redemarcation of the Northern and Eastern
Provinces and for extending more powers to the Tamils in these
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to submit the legal draft of its
devolution package to Parliament soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
