<HEADLINE> Heavy Snow Blankets Eastern US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- One of the worst snowstorms
to hit the nation's east coast in the last 70 years has brought
chaos to the region, at least 14 deaths were blamed on the storm.
</P>
<P>
Blizzards and snowfalls of up to 28 inches in some areas have
shut down airports, caused power failures and closed doors at
retail stores. The storms also kept at home many furloughed
federal workers who were due to report back for duty after a
three-week lay-off.
</P>
<P>
In New Jersey, Delaware, Pennsylvania, Virginia, Maryland, West
Virginia, Kentucky, North Carolina and New York, there were seven
to 28 inches of snow by mid day and it was still snowing.
</P>
<P>
Most airlines canceled or reduced flights into snow-blanketed
cities along the eastern coast, including Washington, New York,
Philadelphia and Newark.
</P>
<P>
Washington's National Airport was closed and the Dulles
International Airport had only one runway open, while New York's
Kennedy and La Guardia airports were both closed. International
flights were rerouted.
</P>
<P>
In North Carolina, sleet and freezing rain cut off power to
residents in many counties in the western part of the coastal
state. In Avery County snow piled up to 28 inches by mid day.
</P>
<P>
In Kentucky, about 18 inches of snow was fallen by mid day. The
Associated Press said a deputy had to hike to her house with a
delivery of special formula milk for her 5-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
In northern Virginia, Washington and Maryland about 2 feet of
snow was on the ground. In Baltimore, there was nearly 25 inches
of snow.
</P>
<P>
The weather service said there hadn't been that much snow in the
area since January 1922.
</P>
<P>
Blizzard warnings were posted for parts of New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Delaware, Washington D.C., and Maryland. In West
Virginia, Ohio, Virginia and Kentucky, heavy snow warnings were
issued.
</P>
<P>
Governors declared state of emergencies in West Virginia,
Maryland and New Jersey. In West Virginia, the National Guard was
placed on alert.
</P>
<P>
Heavy snow also blocked many highways. Tractor-trailer rigs and
buses were ordered off the West Virginia Turnpike through the
rugged southern part of the state. Many trucks voluntarily pulled
off other major highways.
</P>
<P>
Retail stores closed their doors as shoppers stayed home. All
Home Depot stores and many Wal-Mart stores were closed in northern
Virginia. The Rouse Co. closed four of central Maryland's most
popular malls, the first time they had been closed by weather.
</P>
<P>
The snow also kept company employees home from work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
