<HEADLINE> Thailand to Increase Tax on Unleaded Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The excise tax on unleaded
petrol in Thailand may be increased following the ban on the
distribution of leaded petrol which took effect on January 1.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry and the National Energy Policy Office are
considering a tax increase by 75 satang to 3.05 baht (0.122 US
cents) per liter, according to Finance Permanent Secretary
Chatumongkol Sonakul.
</P>
<P>
The new rate on unleaded petrol would be the same as that
previously imposed on leaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government no longer needed to provide
incentives for the use of unleaded petrol under a scheme
introduced in 1992 to improve air quality.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is time for the public to take financial
responsibility for preserving the environment.
</P>
<P>
An Excise Department source said the government might increase
the tax gradually rather than in one jump.
</P>
<P>
During the past four years, promotion of unleaded petrol
through a lower tax rate has cost the government about 20 billion
baht (800 million dollars) in revenue.
</P>
<P>
This year the department expects 54 billion baht (2.16 billion
dollars) from petrol taxes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
