<HEADLINE> Australia's Job Ads Dip in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of job
advertisements declined in Australia in December last year,
pointing to a continued weakness in the country's labor market.
</P>
<P>
The number of employment ads dipped by 1.8 percent after it was
seasonally adjusted in December following a 1.9 percent increase
in the previous month, the ANZ (Australia-New Zealand) Banking
Group Ltd. said in a statement today.
</P>
<P>
In trend terms, the job ads dropped by 0.5 percent in the
month, lower than 0.8 percent in each of the previous three
months.
</P>
<P>
ANZ job advertisement series measures the number of job ads in
major metropolitan daily newspapers and is a barometer of the
country's employment trends.
</P>
<P>
Australia has registered a jobless rate of 8.6 percent in
November and local economists expected that the December figure to
be released on Thursday would be up slightly.
</P>
<P>
The Government is facing a tough task it has pledged of cutting
the jobless rate down to about 5 percent by the end of the
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
