<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Soccer Players Set to Boycott Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Super Eagles soccer
team, enraged over the government's boycott of the African Cup
soccer tournament, will refuse to play for Nigeria in the 1998
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
According to Sunday's independent Concord newspaper, Super
Eagle team members passed a resolution Saturday calling the
government move the "gravest disappointment in our career" and
vowing not to wear Nigeria's colors at the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The Super Eagles won the last biannual African Cup, played in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The government-owned Sunday Times said that the 1996 soccer
season might not be able to take place due to anger from teams
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based African Football Federation had given Nigeria
until Friday midnight to drop the boycott. When Abacha refused,
soccer officials announced that Guinea would replace Nigeria in
the tournament and that exact penalties for Nigeria would be
announced later in the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
