<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-08 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Journalists Face Tough Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Local journalists face a tough
future in the wake of the on-going price war for Chinese-language
newspapers, an industry expert warned.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Tong Kam-piu, chairman of the Hong Kong Journalists'
Association, said the circulation battle has been a rapid
about-turn from the recent boom.
</P>
<P>
"The past two years have seen the media expand very quickly,
and a lot of people were absorbed into the profession with the
emergence of new publications like the Apple Daily, Next Magazine
and Eastweek.
</P>
<P>
"However, what has happened in the past few weeks has been a
swift reversal of fortunes," he was quoted as saying by today's
issue of local newspaper Eastern Express.
</P>
<P>
Since the price war started in mid-December, four newspapers
and two magazines have been closed, which put more than 600 staff
out of work.
</P>
<P>
"Editorial budget will become very tight and we are not
optimistic about annual pay rises for journalists."
</P>
<P>
And Tong predicted a possible plunge of the starting salaries.
"The market is shrinking now while the number of applications is
rising. Although we have not yet seen any examples of staff
salaries being cut, there is a possibility of that happening in
the future," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
