<HEADLINE> Series to Remember Late Premier Zhou Enlai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's provincial television
stations will air a 16-part documentary titled "Zhou Enlai, the
Great Man" starting today, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
On the same day 20 years ago, the country's much venerated
premier passed away.
</P>
<P>
The series will also be broadcast through the national tv
station. Videos will soon be released.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's devotion to the State and charisma as a national leader
made him one of the most beloved political figures in the country.
</P>
<P>
The documentary is a solemn memoir, dense with interviews in
which hundreds of people recall their impression of "our premier."
</P>
<P>
"He was so popular with people that we think everybody could
conjure up a personal image of Zhou," Dai Weiyu, producer and
director of the documentary was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although the whole documentary is about Zhou's life, he seldom
showed up on screen.
</P>
<P>
The eight-hour serial covers important events through Zhou's
life: how he came to know late Chairman Mao Zedong and his
marriage with Deng Yingchao.
</P>
<P>
The program relies on friends and close relations for
information. His doctor Wu Jieping discussed his death from liver
cancer in 1970s. Political figures like Henry Kissinger will also
reflect on Zhou's political life and contributions.
</P>
<P>
The doctor said that documentary does not want to mythicize
Zhou. Finished last February, the documentary was warmly received
in Nanjing and Qingdao where it was televised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
