<HEADLINE> Would-be College Graduates Look for Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 20,000 college seniors
visited the Capital Stadium over the weekend to take part in a
talent fair designed to link job seekers and potential employers,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The fair, sponsored by the Ministry of Personnel, aims to help
central government departments and key state-owned enterprises
recruit college graduates, and establish contracts between the job
hunters and local governments, firms and collective, private and
joint-venture businesses.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 employers staffed 370 stalls to promote their
openings, while students wandered through the displays gathering
information and filling out applications.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Daily published Sunday said that the tables of some
western provinces were not left empty, as they had been at earlier
events. They too were crowded with people seeking information. The
report attributes the change to the government's shift of economic
focus to the western part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Coastal provinces and cities like Shanghai, Fujian and
Shandong, however, remained the hot spots for young job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
To the delight of the local police department, more would-be
graduates have show interests in law enforcement. The city police
plans to enlist 1,000 new officers from among the college
graduates this summer. 
</P>
