<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-07 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More US Women Become Lawyers But Still Earn Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More U.S. women have become
lawyers and judges, making up a larger share in the nation's legal
profession, but they still earn less and get fewer promotions than
men, according to a report released today.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the American Bar Association's
Commission on Women in the Profession, said women now comprise 23
percent of the nation's lawyers and judges and are expected to
make up 40 percent of the legal profession by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
But "barriers persist. Discrimination continues to permeate the
structures, practices and attitudes of the legal profession," the
ABA's CWP panel said.
</P>
<P>
The panel has found that many women are paid less than men and
win fewer promotions, whether they are in private legal practice,
work as corporate lawyers or teach at law schools. The panel also
said sexual harassment still is a problem for many women in the
legal profession.
</P>
<P>
Male lawyers with 10 years and more experience earned an
average of 90,500 dollars a year compared with 68,500 dollars for
women lawyers. Among corporate lawyers, men were paid more than
women at every level of seniority.
</P>
<P>
Women make up almost 13 percent of the partners in private law
firms, but men with similar experience still are promoted more
often.
</P>
<P>
The panel said the legal profession devalues women by
"excluding them from many avenues of career advancement,"
"restricting their access to key clients," and "questioning their
commitment to the firm if they have or want families."
</P>
<P>
But it also noted that despite the existing problems, women
have made significant headway into the profession that was
dominated by men.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, women were only three percent of the nation's lawyers.
But the figure rose to 13 percent by 1985. Last year, they made up
44 percent of all first-year law students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960108.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-07 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Prospects to Be Dim in UK This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Uncertain economic conditions are
expected to hit demand for commercial property in Britain this
year, according to a report here today.
</P>
<P>
A Confederation of British Industry (CBI) survey, to be
published Monday, said that manufacturing and service companies
are becoming more cautious about investing in property as the
slowdown in output starts to bite.
</P>
<P>
The CBI survey, carried out jointly with estate agent
Grimley and covered 804 companies across all sectors, is expected
to show much weaker growth prospects for companies than last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 28 percent of firms are preparing to reduce their
exposure to property over the next six months and only 23 percent
expect to increase their holdings.
</P>
<P>
This reverses the trend established when the CBI last tested
business confidence six months ago.
</P>
<P>
CBI economist Sudhir Junankar said that "with growth
expectations weaker than in our last survey, companies are now
becoming more cautious before deciding to invest in property."
</P>
</TEXT>
